+# Exploration 001 Summary
+
+## Goal
+
+Classify the canonical second-budget seed families for two-triad shared-mode
+clusters.
+
+## What I Tried
+
+- Reduced any connected shared-mode cluster to the representative form
+  `{ (a,b,a+b), (a,c,a+c) }`
+  using the frozen conjugation and triad-relabeling rules.
+- Split the resulting pictures into genuine new seeds versus duplicates,
+  first-budget artifacts, and inert helical decorations.
+
+## Outcome
+
+`succeeded`
+
+## One Key Takeaway
+
+The honest second-budget catalog has two genuinely new geometric families:
+the generic five-orbit shared-mode fan
+`{ (a,b,a+b), (a,c,a+c) }`
+and the four-orbit mirror / parallelogram subfamily
+`{ (a,b,a+b), (a,-b,a-b) }`.
+Any two-triad picture contained entirely in
+`{ ±a, ±b, ±(a+b) }`
+is only a disguised first-budget dead seed.
+
+## Leads Worth Pursuing
+
+- Run recursive exact closure separately on the generic fan and on the
+  mirror/parallelogram subfamily; they fail for different first new targets.
+- Keep re-centered four-orbit drawings merged into the mirror family so the
+  closure audit does not double-count the same seed.
